{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17656342","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17656342"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:11:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:11:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18722"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18722","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18722"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.05,0.35,0.1,0.4]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11454"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79808"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11454","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11454"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18722"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65117"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4934"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"10584"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"26517"},{"type":"contributions","id":"26524"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27287"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79808","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79808"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe Y chromosome is unique to males and contains several genes crucial for male development and fertility. Genetic testing reveals that a 32-year-old man with azoospermia has microdeletions in the azoospermia factor (AZF) regions of his Y chromosome.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the role of Y chromosome genes in male fertility?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Direct sperm capacitation","Maintain blood-testis barrier","Stimulate Leydig cell development","Regulate testosterone synthesis","Control sperm production and maturation"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe Y chromosome contains genes in the AZF regions that \u003Cstrong\u003Econtrol sperm production and maturation\u003C/strong\u003E. These genes are essential for normal spermatogenesis, and their deletion commonly results in severe male infertility or complete absence of sperm production.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERegulate testosterone synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E - Testosterone production is primarily regulated by luteinising hormone (LH), which acts on Leydig cells in the testes. The Y chromosome does not directly control testosterone synthesis; instead, it contains genes that are crucial for male sex determination and spermatogenesis, not hormone regulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDirect sperm capacitation\u003C/strong\u003E - Sperm capacitation occurs in the female reproductive tract and is regulated by local factors\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMaintain blood-testis barrier\u003C/strong\u003E - The blood-testis barrier is maintained by Sertoli cells through genes not located on the Y chromosome\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulate Leydig cell development\u003C/strong\u003E - Leydig cell development is regulated by hormones and genes on autosomes, not the Y chromosome\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe Y chromosome\u0027s AZF regions contain multiple genes required for proper spermatogenesis. Microdeletions in these regions are a significant cause of male infertility, particularly in cases of azoospermia or severe oligospermia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The Y chromosome contains the SRY gene which triggers male sex determination during embryonic development.","Microdeletions in the AZF regions of the Y chromosome commonly cause male infertility.","The Y chromosome contains genes essential for spermatogenesis and male fertility."],"references":["Hall J. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier Health Sciences; 2021.","Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65117"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18722"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"65117","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/65117"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-15T21:59:49+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-15T22:00:16+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11454"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79808"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"